The Fix Region

The fix region contains information for each variant which is sometimes summarized over all samples. The first eight columns of the fixed region are titled CHROM, POS, ID, REF, ALT, QUAL, FILTER and INFO. The function getFIX() will suppress the INFO column by default

head(getFIX(vcf))
##      CHROM              POS   ID REF ALT QUAL     FILTER
## [1,] "Supercontig_1.50" "2"   NA "T" "A" "44.44"  NA

The gt Region

The gt (genotype) region contains information about each variant for each sample The values for each variant and each sample are colon delimited - can store multiple types of genotypes The format of the data is specified by the FORMAT column (column nine)

Distance Matrices

create a pairwise genetic distance matrix for individuals or populations (i.e., groups of individuals) create distance matrix from a genlight object using dist()

x.dist <- dist(x)

also can use bitwise.dist() function to create distance matrices from genlight objs

library(poppr)

chromR Objects

using chromR to locate unusual features in a genome helps visualize the effects of manipulations

Creating chromR

Warning messages indicate that the names in all the data sources do not perfectly match

library(vcfR)

# Find the files.
vcf_file <- system.file("extdata", "pinf_sc50.vcf.gz", package = "pinfsc50")
dna_file <- system.file("extdata", "pinf_sc50.fasta", package = "pinfsc50")
gff_file <- system.file("extdata", "pinf_sc50.gff", package = "pinfsc50")

# Input the files.
vcf <- read.vcfR(vcf_file, verbose = FALSE)
dna <- ape::read.dna(dna_file, format = "fasta")
gff <- read.table(gff_file, sep="\t", quote="")

# Create a chromR object.
chrom <- create.chromR(name="Supercontig", vcf=vcf, seq=dna, ann=gff, verbose=TRUE)
## Names in vcf:
##   Supercontig_1.50
## Names of sequences:

There at least two ways to graphically view the chromR object. The first is plot() which plots histograms of some of data summaries.

# Qual is hard to interpret - most variants of low quality - QUAL not a good parameter for this data to judge variants
# SNP densities is empty b/c the data is creating during the process of chromR objects
plot(chrom)

second plot, called chromo plot, displays the same information as the plot method only it distributes the data along its chromosomal coordinates. *includes a representation of the annotation data

chromoqc(chrom, dp.alpha = 66)

When we observe the chromoqc plot we see that we now have variant densities, nucleotide content as well as a representation of where in our reference we have nucleotides (A, C, G or T) or where we have ambiguous nucleotides.

#  an example of visualizing raw data that has come from a variant caller and other automated sources
chromoqc(chrom, dp.alpha = 66)

We can use this data to create a chromR object and compare it to the above (raw) data.

#vcf <- read.vcfR("data/myVCFdata_filtered.vcf.gz", verbose = FALSE)

vcf <- read.vcfR("data/myVCFdata_filtered.vcf.gz", verbose = FALSE)
chrom <- create.chromR(name="Supercontig", vcf=vcf, seq=dna, ann=gff, verbose=FALSE)
chrom <- proc.chromR(chrom, verbose = FALSE)
chromoqc(chrom, dp.alpha = 66)

# more uniform read depth
# consistent mapping quality

Tabular Summaries

When we process a chromR object, two forms of tabular data are created summaries are made on a per variant basis (sample size, allele counts, heterozygosity, and effective size) summaries made on a per window basis include nucleotide content per window (including missing data so you can adjust window size for analyses if necessary), the number of genic sites per window (when annotation information was provided) and the number of variants per window. window size can be changed w/ win.size

plot(getPOS(vcf), myDiff$Gprimest,  pch = 20, col = "#1E90FF44", xlab = "", ylab = "", ylim = c(0, 1), xaxt = "n")
axis(side = 1, at = seq(0, 1e5, by = 1e4), labels = seq(0, 100, by = 10))
title(xlab='Genomic position (Kbp)')
title(ylab = expression(italic("G'"["ST"])))
